post_text:
We have created an email as a specific point of contact for questions about school reopening. This email will be the best form of communication, as Facebook messages cannot always be monitored.

EDIT: We have developed a Back to School section with Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs) and more at https://www.santarosa.k12.fl.us/.

If you have a question about school reopening, please use BackToSchool@santarosa.k12.fl.us. It is important to understand that we may not have definitive answers yet because of the ever-changing dynamics of this situation and changing guidance from the CDC, FLDOE, and the Florida Department of Health. COVID-19 has impacted the entire world, and we are working cooperatively to maintain a healthy and safe environment for our students.

Students can register now for the July 18th ACT at ACT.org. If your test site is full look at other sites for available space. The July 18th ACT will qualify students for Bright Futures Scholarships.

Register by June 19th to avoid late fees.

Test sites for Santa Rosa County are

Milton High School
Navarre High School
Santa Rosa High
Jay High School
Central School

CDC Guidelines:
All students who test will be screened for COVID-19 symptoms, encouraged to wear masks, and required to sit 6 feet from one another. Test site administrators will also be screened, required to wear masks, and test sites will be held to CDC safety standards and local governments’ “essential business guidelines.”

post_text:
Attention Santa Rosa County Elementary Parents,

For the month of May, all students in grades K-5 will receive their very own copy of the book A Boy Called Bat by Elana K. Arnold along with assignments and activities that meet state standards in all subjects. The ESE Department has taken the book and provided teachers with a variety of resources, scaffolds, and visuals to assist with accessibility. Packet pickup will take place on May 4th and additional information can be received through your indivdual school call out. In addition, students will be able to view some very special guest readers reading aloud from this book through our school district website. We believe you will enjoy the work and activities in this May packet. Thank you for making learning happen at home during this time! Please keep us posted if there's anything we can do as an ESE Department to assist with accessing the content of this book.

Also there are a couple of resources for parents and kids
to better protect children online.
• Common Sense Media (https://www.commonsensemedia.org/) and their “What Is…?” video series for parents.
• Netsmartz (https://www.missingkids.org/NetSmartz) has resources for students of all ages and their parents.

The storm last night caused some issues to roads used for bus routes.
Our plan is to continue to feed at all sites today and run all routes today. Bus delivery will get as close to scheduled bus sites as possible. We may encounter delays due to storm debris in roadways.

We will determine a safe location to distribute curbside meals at PRE since road is blocked due to debris. If it becomes unsafe, we will distribute meals at another location. Watch for changes if necessary.
Thank you for your understanding. Remember that schedules change to Monday, Wednesday and Friday this week. Check the web page under the daily updates to see changes.

post_text: Attention parents of elementary and middle school students, your child has access to MyOn in the ClassLink eBook folder. MyOn is a student-centered, personalized literacy environment that gives students access to more than 6,000 enhanced digital books. Titles are dynamically matched to each individual student's interests, grade and Lexile® reading level. After reading a book in MyOn, students can login to Renaissance in ClassLink to take an AR Quiz from home! Thanks to BHE Media Center for this excellent video.

By order of Governor De Santis, Santa Rosa Schools will close March 23rd through March 27th in response to the COVID-19, virus. post_text:
Visit the district webpage for more updates like this message from Mr. Wyrosdick.
“￼ Santa Rosa District Schools continues work to protect our students and employees. After consultation
with the Santa Rosa Health Department, Center for Disease Control, the Florida High School

Activities Association and guidance from Education Commissioner Corcoran we offer the following
additions to our actions regarding COVID-19/Coronavirus:
Effective March 13, 2020
1. Work related travel for employees is restricted to in-county only
2. Field trips traveling out of county are prohibited
3. In conjunction with the Governor’s request regarding “large gatherings,” currently planned
individual student and athletic extracurricular activities will be reviewed on an individual basis
by the Principal and Director
4. At present, no school closures are planned
*These policies will be reevaluated in 30 days or as more information becomes available”

Our goal is to provide appropriate and timely information regarding individual actions toward combating this virus. Your help and assistance is greatly appreciated.

post_text: National School Counseling Week 2020 is Feb. 3–7. This week highlights the unique contribution of school counselors and the tremendous impact they can have in helping students achieve school and life success. School counselors are certified educators with a minimum of a master's degree in school counseling or related field, making them uniquely qualified to address students’ academic, career, and social/emotional development. Take a moment to thank your local school counselor(s). #NSCW2020

post_text:
Governor Ron DeSantis and Florida Department of Education Commissioner of Education Richard Corcoran recently announced the school districts, universities, colleges and private institutions who have been awarded the Florida Pathways to Career Opportunities Grant.

Our school district, Santa Rosa County District Schools, is one of only two in Northwest Florida to receive this award.

During the 2019 Legislative Session, Governor DeSantis worked with the Florida Legislature to secure historic funding for Florida’s students and families, including $10 million dedicated to career and technical education for the newly created Florida Pathways to Career Opportunities Grant Program. The program provides competitive grants to eligible institutions to create or expand apprenticeship and pre-apprenticeship programs. Of the $10 million in state funding, nearly $3 million still remains.

November 21, 2019 at 9:17 AM ·

The newly created Florida Pathways to Career Opportunities Grant Program supports high schools, career centers and colleges to partner with business and industry and offer high-quality pre-apprenticeship and apprenticeship opportunities.

Santa Rosa County District Schools, Florida added 39 new photos — at Gulf Breeze Middle School.
November 8, 2019 at 11:04 AM · Gulf Breeze, FL ·

Students at Gulf Breeze Middle School created a wall of thank you stars for honorees at their Veterans Day breakfast this morning. In the first photo you see 8th grader Josh Kamm attaching his star. Principal Michael Brandon tells us it is the 14th year the school has followed this patriotic tradition. It was the conception of social studies teacher Grace Freeman who still oversees the creation of the star wall each year. Some students wrote names of their family members who are serving or have served our country. Others penned patriotic poems or cited military history. One creative student went waaaay back in history, having a little fun with the assignment. We saved that one for last to make sure you scrolled through all of the shining stars!

Florida History Mural at GBE

Isn't this mural remarkable? It's spans a long hallway at Gulf Breeze Elementary School. It was painted during the 2007-2008 school year by a very talented local artist named Sheila Van Fossen. Imagine the number of children who have enjoyed this art over the last ten years and learned a lot about our great state too. Given the very recent 1559 archeological discoveries along our local shorelines, we vote for Sheila to come update the part about St. Augustine being the first settlement. :) #rewritinghistory

Schools, Teachers, and Families:
This chart explains the difference between the terms “Secure Facility” and "Lockdown." These two terms will be used by our School Resource Officers to alert and inform the public if there is an emergency at a school that calls for either action. The purpose of this post is to educate all all educational stakeholders so we can be better prepared to coordinate our efforts and work together before potential crisis situations occur. Thank you in advance for sharing and helping spread this safety message.

Throw Back Thursday

This historic photo was taken during the Santa Rosa County Teachers' Institute on August 29, 1917. The teachers are standing in front of the former Milton High School on Canal Street. This building is still in use today for SRCDS School Board meetings. Among those pictured are: A.D. McCall, Mrs. Bessie McCall, Martha McCall Alford, John Diamond, Ruby Robinson, J.D. Smith, Chafin Jernigan, Sidney McCall, Cecil Johnson, Clyde Whitmire, Agnes Stewart, Ross Bass, Ruby Watson Diamond, Lilly Burnett, Frank Simmons, Myra Bergamy, Claudia Bergamy, and A.D. Kean.

Recognize a relative or former teacher? We invite you to contribute what you know about their education careers by posting below.

post_text:
Substitute teachers in our district recently attended a training where three Assistant Principals presented on these three topics: “Classroom Management,” “What to Expect in Sub Folders,” and “Important Areas of Responsibility for Substitutes.” The APs also gained important insights from the subs who provided notes on what substitute teachers need to be more successful when on assignments. This information will be used to make recommendations to all schools for continuous improvement.

The Assistant Principals who participated were: AP Dustin Gray from Pace High School, AP Ashley Flowers from Hobbs Middle School, and AP Monica Garcia from Oriole Beach Elementary School. SAIL Coordinator, Karen Burch, also shared ideas on how substitutes could meet the special needs of students in the SAIL program.

A second training for substitutes in the south end of the county was held Tuesday, October 29h Woodlawn Beach Middle School .

post_text:
The Headless Horseman Seen Gallopiing Down the Hallways at Oriole Beach Elementary School

Second grade students in Carla Urquhart and Danza Riatusso's class created this giant mural depicting the characters and plot of Washington Irving's classic story "The Legend of Sleepy Hollow" first published in 1820.

The teachers’ description of the learning activity follows: “Our second graders spent the week reading The Legend of Sleepy Hollow and created life size character depictions with the legend told from their character’s point of view. They also compared and contrasted the characters and the sequence of events and even made travel brochures persuading visitors to come to Sleepy Hollow.”

post_text:
The Student Government Associations at Pace High School and Milton High School just completed their annual food drive where they collected canned good to donate to The Food Pantry at First Baptist Church of Milton, FL. The Food Pantry serves residents of Santa Rosa County. Each month, over 1,800 people receive food from the Food Pantry.

This year, PHS and MHS students collected 68,155 pounds of food – yet another record year and 8,000 pounds more than they collected last year. The friendly rivalry between the two schools served as motivation for increasing donations. This year Milton High School collected the most food.

Please join us in thanking these high school students for their community service!

Pace High School
Pace High School
Milton High School Official Page
